<br>
1. I suggest you only get one pet at start. This sounds common, but some people (like me) have/had 2 pets at start. This is not a good idea, since you want to save a space to tame wild animals. I always have atleast 1 space open incase I see that little chuba baby outside of Theed.<br>
<br>
2. Fighting can help your Xp when it's low. Right now I have a Greater Sludge Panther, who is 1-2 days old. I take a few hunting missions, and head out. I send out my pet to attack the target, and ready my laser rifle. At the first attack I shoot, and the target falls. I am getting 100 Ch Xp per kill, and if you multiply that by 90(Since I have 2 Explore Missions) that 9,000 Ch Xp per trip. Now, I also fight smaller things that are out there too.<br>
<br>
3. Forge is your best friend. If you have a pet(s) like mine(A greater sludge panther, and a razor cat) they are always hungry. It is good to feed them because like yourself, they heal faster if you do. I have no way to prove this, but I believe that it is true. <br>
<br>
4. The order. I don't know if some of you have a plan about what skills you are going to get, and what branch you are going to max first, but it is good to have a plan on how you are going to climb the tree. For me I find it easier to cover the 'I' skills, then the 'II' skills, and so on. I chose this because if I just climbed the Taming Branch and no others, I could tame all kinds of animals, but have no commands to teach them when they are tamed.<br>
<br>
That's all I can think of now, I'll be back when I think of more.<br>
<br>
Happy Creature Handling<br>
<br>
-Ruka<br>
